value.value: Epithelial layer that is part of the external part of the nose.
An oily substance that prevents evaporation of the eye's tear film.
An exocrine gland that is part of a integumental system.

The spinal accessory nucleus lies within the cervical spinal cord (C1-C5) in the ventral horn. The nucleus ambiguus is classically said to provide the 'cranial component' of the accessory nerve. However, the very existence of this cranial component has been recently questioned and seen as contributing exclusively to the vagus nerve. The terminology continues to be used in describing both human anatomy, and that of other animals.
A blood vessel that supplies or drains an ear.
A nucleus in the ventral part of the anterior horn of the sacral region of the spinal cord that is the origin of the pudendal nerve.

label.value: strand of hair on external ear

value.value: The single bud-like invagination of the conjunctival fornix epithelium at the temporal aspect of the eye that signals lacrimal gland formation (Int Rev Cytol. 1996;168:1-80. Cell biology of the harderian gland).
An aqueous substance that covers the anterior surface of the eyeball, keeping the cornea wet.
A portion of organism substance that is secreted by a reproductive gland.

label.value: inferior palpebral branch of infra-orbital nerve

value.value: A nerve that innervates a lower eyelid and is a branch of the infra-orbital branch of the maxillary nerve.
A nerve that innervates an eyelid and is a branch of the infra-orbital branch of the maxillary nerve.
A nerve that innervates a lower eyelid.
A nerve that innervates an upper eyelid.
A branch of the ciliary ganglion that innervates the ciliary muscles, the iris, and the tunics of the eyeball.
Single layer of a laminar structure, identified by different density, arrangement or size of cells and processes arranged in flattened layers or lamina[CUMBO].
Serous membrane layer that is adjacent to and lines an organ.
Serous membrane layer that lines to a body cavity.
The layer of endometrial epithelium adjacent to the uterine cavity.
A blood vessel of the placenta.
A mammary gland duct that is part of a male organism. This structure typically regresses.
A specific region of the foregut into the area in which the lung will develop.
A set of neural structures that subserve a specific function, e.g., visual system.

label.value: white matter of the cerebellar cortex

value.value: White matter that lies deep to the granular cell layer of the cerebellar cortex. It contains afferents to the cerebellar cortex and axons that run between the cerebellar cortex and the deep cerebellar nuclei.
The part of the central nervous system that is involved with movement.

definition.value: It consists of the pyramidal and extrapyramidal system

value.value: The sensory system for the sense of proprioception.
A taste bud that is located on the soft palate, in the roof of the mouth.
Any organ that is the primary organ of vocalization behavior. Examples: The laryngeal vocal cord (humans), the syrinx (birds).
An embryonic or larval epithelium that is committed to form part of the nervous system.
An epithelium that is undergoing proliferation to provide large numbers of neuronal cells.
A neuroepithelium some of whose cells are undergoing terminal differentiation to become neuronal cells.
The layer of the developing cerebral cortex that is formed from the first cohort of neurons to migrate out of the cortical ventricular zone; split by the second wave into marginal zone and subplate.

Any of the cranial nerves, or their central nervous system analogs (the optic tract, the epiphyseal tract). These analogs are not true nerves, and are instead evaginated sensory afferents emanating from the brain.
A cranial nerve fiber tract that innervates the parietal eye.

definition.value: This should be classified as an evaginated sensory afferents rather than cranial nerves, as they are part of the CNS[ISBN:0471888893]
